text: This trailer's awful. The premise is anything but creative. Even scenes in the trailer were ripping off from horror movies... come on, his shadow and his hand pressed against the shower window? At the end where Michael Ealy is under the bed and turns to face the camera I was cracking up.¬†  Honestly, I hate that some women eat this shit up. It's sad that hollywood cashes in on this taboo romance shit. There's NO SUCH THING AS A PERFECT GUY, but the fact that these writers and directors would premise a "perfect guy" on the qualities of sex, cockblocking another guy at a bar, and buying football tickets to take impress a girl's dad instead of actual character, wisdom, and ambition is pathetic enough for me to understand that they know their audience for this type of shit.  I am not one to shit on art, but the lack of originality and the surface-deep conflict of this film makes it difficult for me to see it as that. I just wish that recognizable black male leads like Ealy and Morris Chestnut could reach higher than that by now.

text: Lol, they just showed the entire movie in the trailer. No need to watch it.  Here's what I think it happens: She breaks up with her ex. She knows that new guy. He seems to be the perfect guy until something happens and then he turns into some kind of maniac. She gets scared and goes to look for her ex, yeah, there was someone worse than her ex. They come back, but her new ex ( the ex perfect guy ) keeps harassing both of them. She goes to ask for help from the cops. Cops say they can't do anything until something really bad happens. I bet the girl has that best friend that may be her neighbour. So, the perfect bad guy keeps harassing everyone, he kills the female neighbour. I bet Morris Chestnut bites the dust halfway too, so the movie obviously must end with the final fight between the woman and the perfect guy. The woman should have a gun ( I assume a shotgun, based on a pic from imdb ). Bad guy manages to take away her gun and they fight until she finally kills him. Then, like every movie, the cops finally arrive when everything is over.  Now tell me I'm wrong.
